“In their view, an older woman is automatically [seen as] an older virgin, waiting to be raped by gangs. They fear that people will target them and fear their reputation,” informed my tutor. Such old beliefs stress women that marriage is the ultimate aim in life.

This lack of understanding, however, is not only seen among tribal communities in rural areas but extends to those in urban areas as well. A well-to-do Muslim lady, who is married to a Hindu Indian man, expressed her ignorance: “I know there is Sharia law, but to differentiate between what’s acceptable or not is not always clear cut.”

While the government does offer alternative sources of funding, these options do not address all needs – the support group considered they were just “treading water”. One woman said: “I can’t get a job because my family is looking for a man [to propose] to me…there is this pressure on the woman [to find a suitable match] until she is 40, then suddenly no one wants her, and she is considered [to be] ‘over the hill’.”
